  "updated_summary": "The narrative begins with an aerial view of Emirates Stadium and a title card, 'THE UNITED STORY SUMMER 2003', accompanied by a dramatic orchestral score. A narrator reveals that Manchester United's acquisition of Cristiano Ronaldo involved significant pre-planning, contrary to the belief that it stemmed solely from his performance against them in August 2003. During the 2002-2003 season, Sir Alex Ferguson's assistant, Carlos Queiroz, received reports on Ronaldo and recognized the urgency for United to act. Queiroz, identified as 'ASSISTANT MANAGER - UNITED', stated, \"I informed Alex about Cristiano.\" The video highlights Queiroz's past as Sporting Lisbon's manager ('94-96'), where he established connections and arranged an exchange of methodologies, symbolized by a split-screen graphic of the Manchester United and Sporting CP crests with bidirectional arrows. Jim Ryan, Reserve Team Coach, informed Ferguson about Ronaldo, noting, \"I've seen a player... I think he's a winger, but he's playing as a central striker with the youth team,\" and advised, \"I wouldn't wait long to declare our interest. There will be other clubs after him.\" Ferguson arranged for Ryan to visit Sporting Lisbon and subsequently proposed signing Ronaldo with a loan-back clause, a common condition sought by other major clubs like Juventus, Real Madrid, Liverpool, Arsenal, Barcelona, and Valencia. A friendly match was scheduled to celebrate the opening of Sporting's new stadium, Estádio José Alvalade, on August 6, 2003, as part of a special agreement between the clubs. The segment concludes by showing Ferguson and Jorge Mendes, described as the man in sunglasses, meeting on August 5, 2003, the day before the friendly, emphasizing the critical timing of United's intensified pursuit of Cristiano Ronaldo."
